ITEM 1 — "Balance peer delegation" (managed-worker-7473 got 22 of 25
delegated tasks). Real code-level cause found, flagged-not-fixed. All three
peer pickers (pickLightestIdlePeer, pickPeerByRole, pickExecutor in
server/src/lib/peers.ts, lines ~53-117) sort candidates by inflightJobs
ascending and take index 0. Array.prototype.sort is stable, so whenever both
workers are idle (inflight 0 — the common case for a lightly loaded fleet),
the tie is always broken by pollPeers() registration order, and the same
peer (7473) wins every time. 7474's 3 tasks likely landed only while 7473
was mid-job. This is not a config knob; there are no delegation rules to
"configure" as the reflection suggests. Suggested fix when the tree is
clean: break inflight ties with rotation or random choice (e.g. sort key
(inflight, jitter) or a module-level round-robin cursor) in all three
pickers, plus a unit test that two idle peers each receive work across
repeated picks. Small, contained change.

ITEM 2 — "Redistribute employee tasks from Milo" (30 of 50
employee-attributed tasks). Confirmed real skew but it is a workload/config
decision, not a bug — no code change appropriate. Milo is the
multimedia-producer persona (server/src/lib/personas.ts:676). Persona
selection is either explicit (operator/schedule names the persona) or
auto-routed by pickPersonaForTask (server/src/lib/persona-router.ts:344),
which only fires above a confidence floor of 2 and falls through to clawbot
on ties — it does not dogpile one persona by accident. The day's work was
genuinely media-heavy (media.image ran 11 times; multimedia-package was the
top skill at 5 runs), so Milo's share reflects what was asked, and Cora/
Bram/Aria are different specialists — silently reassigning media work to
them would change output quality. If the operator wants routine general
tasks spread out, that's a schedule/template authoring choice (which persona
each scheduled task names), not something an unattended run should decide.
No action taken.

ITEM 3 — "Refine skill metadata for send-attachment / vault-organization"
(and human-handoff, all matched at score 15). Genuine metadata gap,
flagged-not-fixed because of the stop condition. Score 15 in the picker
(server/src/lib/skills.ts, scoring at ~lines 341-377) means exactly one
keyword pattern hit and ZERO intent match — an intent match adds 20+
specificity, so these skills were selected on keywords alone because the
task's classified intent isn't in their applies_to lists:
send-attachment has [draft-email, draft-other], vault-organization has
[research, summarize, draft-other], human-handoff has [plan, draft-other].
All three runs still succeeded (successRate 1.0), so this is routing
robustness, not a failure. Suggested fix when the tree is clean: check what
intents the classifier actually emitted for those jobs and add them to the
respective applies_to frontmatter (server/src/skills/send-attachment.md,
vault-organization.md, human-handoff.md); note the keyword patterns
themselves were already sharpened on 2026-07-08 and 2026-07-09 per comments
in skills.ts, so the remaining gap is the intent side, not more regexes.

